# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "Bug hunt: silent AttributeError + report bugs + fey-garden shape (build 392). Five bugs in the same shape as the b385 Potion.use() crash (and surfaced because that fix made me audit the pattern). (1) Shard of Battle / Shard of Eternity passive bonuses (legendary-monster rewards in combat.py:962) wrote `setattr(player_character, 'base_attack', player_character.base_attack + 3)` -- Character stores those as `_base_attack` / `_base_defense`, so reading the public name raised AttributeError, the lambda crashed, and the shard's +3 attack / +5 defense was never applied. Player got the shard in their bag but with no actual stat bump. (2) The Void altar sacrifice reward (room_actions.py:314) wrote to `player_character._max_mana` -- which doesn't exist; max_mana is a computed @property. The +2 max MP boon silently no-op'd; the hunger-fill path was fine. (3) Same _max_mana AttributeError at Solara T3 pray (room_actions.py:353). The +10 max MP part of the capstone never applied. (4) Inline fey-garden loot_table at room_actions.py:2558 had tuple shape `(name, effect_type, magnitude, value, description)` but the Ingredient constructor reads `(description=[1], value=[2], level=[3])` -- so every harvested Moonbell Flower came out with description='mana_boost', value=magnitude (1-3 gold ~free), level=value (15-50 absurdly over-tier). Re-shaped to the canonical `(name, desc, value, level, chance)` matching GARDEN_INGREDIENTS. (5) HTML report inventory truncation at playtest_report.py:1573: `for i in inv[:24]` dropped late-game slots. Crafted sausages routinely land at slot 60+ and vanished from the rendered table. Removed cap. (6) Vendor 'gold spent' column inflated at playtest_report.py:1508: `cur[1] + price * c` -- but the parsed log line 'You bought N x ITEM for P gold' carries P = `new_item.calculated_value` (total stack cost), not per-unit. Bug surfaced on Flare bundles where count=5 multiplied the already-total price by 5. Fix: drop the `* c`.",
    "Hard floor cap on tomb_elite at z>=5 (build 391). Single-line spawn-time fix in dungeon.py:setup_dungeons_and_tombs -- tombs on F1-F4 now still get four floor-leveled undead guardians, but no +1-level 1.3x-stat elite. The b389 death-cause sweep attributed 3/17 deaths (~18%) to ELITE UNDEAD WRAITH / SPECTER at F2-F5: a F3 elite Wraith has 32 atk * 1.3 = 41 raw, kills an L3 player (def~5 HP~50) in 2 rounds. Smart-policy flee gate fires correctly but the parting blow + adjacent re-engage on tight early floors finish under-levelled agents anyway. The b390 T-tile wayfinder avoid and heal-before-flee defended after-the-fact; this cap removes the trap at spawn time. By F5 the player has ~60-80 HP and Stone Skin / +DEF gear in reach, so the elite threshold lines up with the level where the +1-level 1.3x-stat tier is survivable. Cleaner than the b390 wayfinder + flee tweaks because it operates at the property-flagging step in dungeon.py:688 before the monster object exists, so no harness or combat-policy code needs to know about the cap.",
    "Tomb-tile wayfinder avoid + narrow heal-before-flee (build 390). Investigation into deep-floor mortality from the handoff. The b389 sweep revealed monster scaling isn't the killer -- Hardened+ encounters are only 2% of combats with 0 deaths. The real lethal patterns: tomb elite undead at F2-F4 (3/17 baseline deaths to ELITE UNDEAD WRAITH / SPECTER) and brutal parting blows on flee. Two playtest_harness.py interventions: (1) T-tile wayfinder avoid -- under-levelled agents (pc.level < pc.floor + 3, mirrors blocked_guardian_dirs gate) no longer target discovered tomb tiles, so the BFS first_step won't pull them toward elite-guardian corners. Trapped exception drops the avoid when no D is reachable so the agent can still pray for boons. (2) Heal-before-flee in combat_mode -- when monster_too_tough AND HP between 50-65% AND a heal pot is in bag, drink first then flee next turn. Tighter than full HP<80% gate because heals cap at max_hp (>65% wastes the heal) and HP<50% the existing HP-low gate already fires. Both interventions are defensive code grounded in the death-cause analysis; n=18 sweep variance (+/-2 deaths between runs) is too noisy to show statistically clean improvement, but the changes are theoretically sound and don't regress mean floor (human 5.33 / elf 3.50 / dwarf 5.50, comparable to b389).",
    "Weighted garden harvest + fey-garden TypeError fix (build 389). Two coordinated changes that unblock the crafting pipeline at the ingredient supply side. (1) GARDEN_INGREDIENTS at item_templates.py:357 carries a 5th tuple field (`chance`: 0.15 for common herbs, 0.10 uncommon, 0.02-0.03 rare) that was added with clear intent but never wired up -- room_actions.py:process_garden_action used `random.choice(loot_table)` which gives uniform weight. Dragon Scale (3% intended) dropped as often as Moonpetal (15% intended), starving the lembas / sausage recipes that key on the four common herbs (Moonpetal / Starbloom / Healing Moss / Fire Root). Switched to `random.choices(loot_table, weights=...)` so common-ingredient density doubles per garden visit. (2) The inline fey-garden loot table at room_actions.py:2548 puts the DESCRIPTION string in slot [4] (not a chance float), so blindly extracting weights would crash random.choices with TypeError: can only concatenate str (not 'float') to str -- the harness swallows it silently and the fey garden harvest fails. Added an isinstance check: weights only applied when all 5th-field values are numeric, otherwise fall back to uniform. Result: 18 craft entries across the 18-run sweep (vs 11 in b388, +64%), distributed across all three races (human 4, elf 6, dwarf 8). 0 errors in the sweep.",
    "Game-loop crafting trigger (build 388). Defense-in-depth so the agent enters inventory for crafting even when no other inventory trigger fires. Pre-fix, the crafting cascade only fired opportunistically -- when the agent entered inventory for cooking / eating / stat-alloc / etc. Diagnostic: dwarf seed=1 had 21 turns where _pick_craftable_food returned a craftable recipe but only 2 crafting_mode entries, so 19 missed opportunities. New game_loop gate at playtest_harness.py:3032 (right after the cooking gate) opens inventory when (Curing Kit + cooked meat) OR (elf race + ingredients) AND hunger >= 30 AND _pick_craftable_food returns a recipe. Gated on last_action not in (i, x, c) so the post-craft re-entry doesn't loop. Sweep impact in current seed set is neutral (11 craft entries before vs after) because the existing inventory cascade already catches all opportunities IF the agent happens to enter inventory for any reason. The new trigger reduces craft LATENCY -- agents that have materials but no other reason to open inventory can now craft directly. Mean floors unchanged, 0 errors, no regression.",
    "Spell-buy at vendors + memorization policy + harness dispatch (build 387). Closes the handoff's 'spellbook-reading policy gap' -- pre-fix, humans / dwarves could only ever cast their starter cantrip (humans: Mind Touch, dwarves: none). Vendors stock 0-2 random spells per visit but the smart policy never bought them, and even if it had, no policy hook entered spell_memorization_mode to convert an owned Spell into a castable one. Four coordinated changes in playtest_harness.py: (1) Expose pc.get_max_memorized_spell_slots() and pc.get_used_spell_slots() as max_spell_slots / used_spell_slots in player obs so the policy can read its INT-gated capacity. (2) New spell_inventory obs field (parallel to inventory but in get_spell_inventory insertion order, NOT sorted) -- the spell_memorization_mode handler at combat.py:1454 indexes m<N> off this order, so the policy must mirror it. (3) Inventory-mode trigger: when free_spell_slots > 0 AND an identified non-cantrip unmemorized spell fits the slot budget, return 'm' to enter spell_memorization_mode. Sits between the stat-allocation trigger and cooking. (4) spell_memorization_mode policy handler: scores candidates as healing (10000+power) > damage (5000+power*10/mana_cost) > buff/utility (1000), picks the highest-scoring spell that fits free slots, sends m<N>. Plus harness dispatch for spell_memorization_mode (was missing, would have stuck the agent if any path put them there). Vendor branch gets a spell-buy gate gated on `can_cast` (excludes dwarves; gates pre-INT-13 humans), capped at 5 distinct spell names. Smoke (seed=5 human +10 INT): spells=1 -> m3 -> spells=2 at T102, mode exits cleanly to inventory then game_loop.",
    "Basic-tier permanent elixirs ~50% price cut (build 386). The b385 validation sweep confirmed the pipeline works end-to-end (1 elixir bought + drunk cleanly, 0 AttributeError crashes across 27,800 turns, 0 leftovers in bag), but only 1 of 4 stocked elixirs got purchased. Three missed buys were all gold-gated: mid-game agents typically have 700-1100g per vendor visit after Curing Kit + Rations + stockpile, leaving < 800g for the elixir. Cut basic-tier prices ~50%: Might / Grace / Brilliance 800g -> 400g, Vitality 1200g -> 600g. Applied consistently at vendor.py:357-378 (F4+ regular vendor stock), vendor.py:1036-1039 (Magic Shoppe basic tier), items.py:4267-4276 (POTION_TEMPLATES), and item_templates.py:1022-1031 (mirror). Greater (+4, 2000g) and Supreme (+6, 5000g) tiers unchanged -- the price gap between tiers preserves the 'permanent elixirs feel earned' progression. At 400g a typical F5+ agent with 600-900g post-stockpile can afford one elixir per vendor visit when stocked, lifting expected drinks/sweep from b385's 1/12 toward the original goal of ~4/12.",
    "Basic permanent elixirs at F4+ vendors + buy priority + crash fix (build 385). Three coordinated changes after the b384 sweep exposed three layered bugs. (1) Permanent elixirs only spawned in F20+ Magic Shoppes (15% per floor) and 0/18 sweep agents reached F20 -- the b380 'Elixir of Brilliance level gate dropped to 4' only touched the item-template eligibility tier, not actual placement. Fix in vendor.py:Vendor.__init__: 25% chance per F4+ regular vendor to stock one of four basic-tier elixirs (Elixir of Might / Grace / Brilliance / Vitality, level 4, 800g / 1200g). Greater (+4) and Supreme (+6) tiers stay Magic-Shoppe-only. (2) Smart policy was stocking 6x Healing Potions before reaching the buff-potion buy check, leaving < 800g for the elixir at every visit. Fix in playtest_harness.py: new permanent-elixir buy gate hoisted ABOVE the stockpile loop (after Cooking + Curing Kit, before Rations) -- agent buys one of each unowned permanent type on sight, no MAGIC_RESERVE cushion. (3) Drinking Elixir of Might / Defense crashed mid-effect with AttributeError ('Character' has no 'base_attack' / 'base_defense'). Bug was pre-existing in items.py:Potion.use() but invisible until b384/b385 actually drank one. The character.strength += effect ran (visible STR change) before the AttributeError, which the harness swallowed silently, so `consumed = ...` was never assigned and remove_item never called -- the elixir stayed in inventory, dripping +2 STR per re-drink turn (seed=1 human ran STR up to 615). Fix in items.py: `character.base_attack` -> `character._base_attack`, `character.base_defense` -> `character._base_defense` (Character stores as private). Verified: seed=1 human now drinks 4 Elixirs of Might across F4-F11 = +8 STR, all consumed cleanly, 0 elixirs left in bag.",
]
